service at it's core and requires heavy Capex expenses.
I used to own BJS (the pressure pumping unit of BHI) before it was taken out
and I did not feel that the economics are good unless there are capacity
constraints. What I expect now to happens, is that not only demand will fall
for pressure pumping services, but prices will fall as well, which will lead to
a double whammy in revenues and margins.

I think I would buy BHI probably in the 30's assigning only little value to the
pressure pumping business, but I would have to run the numbers again. BHI
problems will be shared by many service companies that have been benefiting
from the fracking boom, imo. Those without proprietary products lines like BHI,
will be hurt even more (the BAS, CJES and alike companies as well as the
drillers).
